The "alternative release scenarios" prepared and made a part of the RMP are as follows.  For chlorine, the scenario is a hole in a transfer line resulting in a release of 7.7 lbs/minute for a duration of 15 minutes.  For hydrazine, it is a hole in a transfer line resulting in a release of 30 lbs./minute onto the ground for a duration of ten minutes.

A comprehensive program described in a number of manuals and procedures designed to prevent accidental releases of any chemicals used at the plant has been in place for many years and includes:

1.  Process safety information located throughout the plant;
2.  Process hazard reviews conducted on all manufacturing processes;
3.  Detailed written operating procedures that provide clear instructions for safe operation of each process;
4.  Regular employee training on process operating procedures, safety, emergency operation/shutdown, and chemical hazard communication;
5.   Maintaining mechanical integrity of process equipment through regular inspection, testing and preventive maintenance;
6.  Management of changes to process chemicals, technology, equipment and procedures to insure continued safe operation:
7.  Pre-start up safety reviews for new or modified processes;
8.  Periodic compliance reviews to evaluate whether procedures and practices to prevent accidental releases are adequate and are being followed;
9.  Routine investigation of any incidents which resulted in, or could have resulted in, a release of chemicals;
